review_blob: a couple days ago I purchased a sixer of black butte porter and after pouring a nice glass of what I though was the porter I was surprised by something even more roasty and flavorful.  apparently the customer who last purchased some of this stout made a mixed six with the porter I bought.  Nice!

Pours a transparent medium mahogany and presents a bit of a lacquerish aroma as well.  I cant quite decide if the taste of of rotten, sour cherries or sour, rotten cherries, but it doesnt matter--this is one fine beer!!!
lemony goodness, just a hint of pine-cone, assertive cattiness, but not offputting; subtly complex straight forward pale ale.
bread, grass, barnyard, skunky, golden, hazy, frothy, rocky head, medium sweetness, medium bitterness, medium sourness, paper napkin, medium body, slick feel, lively, fizzy, fizzy,

this was a fun beer and a nice break from the all ipa and stout diet i have been on recently.   lots of nice maltiness to chew through, i may as well call it toasty as in the commercial deScription, but i did not detect the toasted hops that bluemooner describes below.
this is a nice stout.  it was less roasty than i expected but very complex with a pleasant smokiness and light fruity flavor.
this one i really enjoyed.  it satisfied my sweet tooth without getting gross.  smells like musty chocolate bread and tastes like toffee.  the high carbonation balanced the sweetness very nicely.
very sweet......a little undercarbonated......taste is an interesting charred caramel apple.....other than that it is just boozy and boring.

too harsh....this yellow-orange beer has too much residual sugar and is way too abrasive in the flavor department.  im not sure if it is the hop combination or what, but the pine-sol flavor comes on strong.  give me a stone ipa any day
explodes with C-hop aroma, but the the flavor does not live up to the smell.  there are plenty of hops, but the finish is an unpleasant honey/diet coke flavor.  metallic and sticky.
citrus and pine, nice grainy malt backbone, very similar to SNPA.  not a big ipa, but nice hoppy and drinkable

biscuity and soapy, way too sweet, like rotten plum cough syrup.  if this had some tartness it would be nice, but the finish was way too sweet for me.  oh, and it was a bit flat as well.  interesting, but not something i will go back to.
i have to say i was a little disappointed with this one.  there wasnt anything really wrong with it, it just lacked the complexity that i was looking for.  clean, dry, fizzy, just not funky enough
the cork says 2008--effervescent and thirst quenching.  this beer smells like Christmas morning.  light, fruity, spicy, a little skunky...
a very clean tasting ipa from rogue.  color is light to medium yellow, tastes like an ipa, not terribly interesting.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: orangy glowing floral citrus and sweet ipa.  surfs up dude....................
very sweet, big doppelbock.  commercial deScription is accurate, however i found it to be too sweet for my tastes.
nicely balanced coffee beer.
didnt understand this one.  it was rather unattractive with a dirty murky brown color, and tasted stale.  I think they just over did the malt bill for this beer.  unpleasant.
tastes like sweet red wine and dried apricots with the signature unibrew yeasty goodness.  big, big beer with a very slight tart finish.......nice........oh yeah, hint of chocolate
smooth malty slightly fruity dark ale.  did not detect the smoke flavor from the deScription.
this big stout does is sweet and smooth without many of the problems associated with big beers.   nice rich aroma and clean sweet malty roasty smooth flavor.

there is not much i can add to the commercial deScription of this beer.  it was beautifully done.  refreshing and a pleasure to drink.  i did not however find this beer as piney as the many of the other reviewers
beer_name: Great Divide Fresh Hop Pale Ale

review_blob: this is a nice iipa, it shares some characteristics with ruination (light straw color, but there is no malt backbone in this ale, and the bitterness is sharp on the back of the tongue.  i enjoyed this, but i would rather just have a hopdevil

i appreciate the creative attempt boston beer co made formulating this interesting lager, but it didnt work.  way too much astringent hop bitterness.  appearance is a nice hazy glowing orange. aftertaste is like stale armpit sweat, but not in a bad way...what is an imperial pilsner?  when i think of a big pilsner duvel comes to mind even though it is an ale i think it has the soul of a nice pilsner and is about the same abv as this mess.
fresh roasted chocolaty coffee that will get me drunk.   i like how this beer is a little overcarbonated for the style.  somehow it works.
how have i not rated this jewel.  it has everything that is missing from every mediocre ipa i have ever drank.  it smells better than fresh hops on the bine and tastes better than beer.
very clean, tastes like lager, the appearance points are for the cool picture on the bottle.
beer_name: Grand Teton Au Naturale (Organic Blonde Ale)

review_blob: grassy with some enjoyable yeastiness.  it is an american wheat hefe whatever, what do you think it tastes like?
why the low ratings, this was probably the best of the special releases i picked up from teton.  comercial deScription is accurate.  good lager, not heavy or harsh despite the 7% abv
not a ton of sourness, this was quite an interesting beer, and it was a gusher when i popped the bottle.  wine like flavors and then i get a little lost.
actually a really big beer for the diminutive 5.5 abv flavor is very sharp and a little astringent.
good ipa enjoyed at the taproom in bozeman.  alcohol is a little too apparent, but plenty of hops are there
on draft at the almost friendly taproom in bozeman.  one of my 3 pints allowed for the day.  i think this was hoppier than other dark ales in this region of the country.  well done

on this one i tend to agree with many of the other raters.  was not overwhelmed by this beer, but it was ok.  definately earthy(see dirty) and sweet.  kind of makes me think it was made from extract for some reason.

this is a combined rating.  this beer was availible both on regular draft an nitro tap  the summer of 2007.  the nitro was boring, but as it hid much of the hop character made ipa accessible to hop haters.  the regular draft was a solid brewpub ipa. reminded me of a bigger version of snpa.  i even went home with a growler of it.
fun beer to drink.  nice packaging.  I would have like more chocolate notes, but the understated caramel notes do this one well until it warms. then it falls a little flat.
beer_name: Kettle House Cold Smoke Scotch Ale

review_blob: slightly catty, grapefruity flavor lacking the proper malt scaffold to balance the flavor.  it is however dry and poundable.  along with being the best bang for the buck at the mammoth employee pub.  appearance marks are due to the cool can. (just because it is a can, graphics are sort of lame)

Im surprised there are not more ratings for this beer.  available in sixers in and around yellowstone park.  nice charred caramel malt taste.  as argo noted, cola and light sourness is a good deScription of the taste of this beer, but unlike him i enjoyed it.  I visited the brewpub and this beer really isnt a good representation of the local flavor.  the bar had more interesting offerings.
clean taste although somewhat tinny.  just an easy drinking golden ale.
good session ipa if you are out west and in need of a hop injection.  I went through many of these over the summer of 07

on tap at Medici, normal ($3 full 12oz. pour) big with the hops even for an impy stout.  very floral. could drink these all night every night, all of the flavor and balance, with none of the sticky cloying sweetness of other big stouts.

the came off as an undrinkable butterbomb.  diacetyl is all i can detect in this dark ale with some mix of dark malts in the finish.  no hop presence at all.  for a rotating release stout i just dont get where they were going with this beer.
I just dont get this beer.  it is their biggest regular offering, but is bland and slightly astringent.  barely drinkable....boring
beer_name: Blue Cat Big Bad Dog Olde English Ale

review_blob: uncompromising pale ale.  I think they change the hop bill on this one from time to time.  the character was different than i remember from my last sample a couple of years ago.  i think i detected simcoe in the flavor, but i might just have simcoe on the brain.....anyways this was good and hoppy and get some if you are in down town davenport
solid offering from front street brewery.  no surprised, but definitely not disappointing.
good replacement for the uncommon as they were out of my beloved coffee stout when i visited. solid roasty toasty smooth goodness
did they forget they forget the  yeast?   seriously this is way sweet, but still good and very chocolaty if that is your thing.

bottle provided by noblesquirrel.  I was scared after the pour provided nothing in the way of carbonation, but this beer redeemed itself with its amazing balance. similar to speedway, but with less hops and less in your face coffee.  very nice.
